<subSubSection id="C36965D095611873FF0BB32E10E11CE9" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="29" pageId="5" pageNumber="28" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BCC365B95611870FF0BB32E10AF1F58" blockId="5.[174,1234,1498,1837]" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">
D i s t r i b u t i o n. Europe (almost everywhere), the Caucasus, Transcaucasia, 
<collectingCountry id="F36476CB95611870FB6DB32F17941F39" box="[1157,1233,1554,1580]" name="Russia" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">Russia</collectingCountry>
(Southern Siberia, Far East), 
<collectingCountry id="F36476CB95611870FDE8B30F11C31F59" box="[512,646,1586,1612]" name="Turkey" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">Asia Minor</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFE24BAA95611870FD7DB30F100C1F59" author="Baraniak, E." box="[661,841,1586,1612]" pageId="5" pageNumber="28" pagination="1 - 122" refId="ref2422" refString="Baraniak, E. 2007. Taxonomic revision of the genus Plutella Schrank, 1802 (Lepidoptera: Plutellidae) from the Palaearctic region with notes on its phylogeny. Polskie Pismo Entomologiczne. 76, Suppl., 1 - 122." type="book chapter" year="2007">Baraniak, 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE24BAA95611870FCBBB30F10981F58" author="Sinev, S. Y." box="[851,989,1586,1613]" pageId="5" pageNumber="28" pagination="45 - 58" refId="ref2729" refString="Sinev, S. Y. 2008. Families: Yponomeutidae, Argyresthiidae, Plutellidae, Ypsolophidae. Catalogue of the Lepidoptera of Russia. KMK Press, St. Petersburg, Moscow, 45 - 58 [In Russian]." type="book chapter" year="2008">Sinev, 2008</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCC365B95611870FF0BB36E12D31FD8" blockId="5.[174,1234,1498,1837]" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">
D i a g n o s i s. Wingspan 
<quantity id="4C8B9BBE95611870FDF1B36F11E41F78" box="[537,673,1618,1645]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="28" unit="mm" value="15.0" valueMax="18.0" valueMin="12.0">12–18 mm</quantity>
. Head white dusted with pale grey-brownish coloration. Labial palpi bent, the middle segment with a distinct tuft of brownish scales. Forewings white-yellowish with brownish pattern which consists stripes and dots (
<figureCitation id="13482ADE95611870FB65B3AF17891FB8" box="[1165,1228,1682,1709]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[174,207,1289,1311]" captionTargetBox="[331,1074,184,1255]" captionTargetId="figure-183@5.[326,1083,166,1269]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 5. Pseudoplutella porrectella: 1 — moth (habitus, dorsal); 2 — male genitalia (lateral view); 3 — aedeagus; 4 — bursa copulatrix." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6414511" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6414511/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">fig. 5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13482ADE95611870FF46B38F13F91FD9" box="[174,188,1714,1740]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="1.[174,207,1408,1430]" captionTargetBox="[325,1069,174,1369]" captionTargetId="figure-159@1.[321,1078,171,1383]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Fig. 1. Argyresthia kurenzovi: 1 — forewing pattern; 2–4 — male genitalia (2 — ventral view, 3 — ventral plate, 4 — aedeagus); 5 — female genitalia; 6 — bursa copulatrix with signum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6414497" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6414497/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis id="B907EA4995611870FF46B38F13F91FD9" box="[174,188,1714,1740]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">1</emphasis>
</figureCitation>
). Hindwings grey.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCC365B95611870FF0BB3EF12581E38" blockId="5.[174,1234,1498,1837]" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">
Male genitalia (
<figureCitation id="13482ADE95611870FE4AB3EF12A61FF8" box="[418,483,1746,1773]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[174,207,1289,1311]" captionTargetBox="[331,1074,184,1255]" captionTargetId="figure-183@5.[326,1083,166,1269]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 5. Pseudoplutella porrectella: 1 — moth (habitus, dorsal); 2 — male genitalia (lateral view); 3 — aedeagus; 4 — bursa copulatrix." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6414511" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6414511/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">fig. 5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13482ADE95611870FE1CB3EF11471FF9" box="[500,514,1746,1772]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[166,199,1105,1127]" captionTargetBox="[322,1065,191,1089]" captionTargetId="figure-253@2.[317,1074,174,1089]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 2. Argyresthia communana: 1 — forewing pattern; 2–4 — male genitalia (2 — ventral plate, 3 — valva, 4 — aedeagus); 5 — bursa copulatrix." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6414501" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6414501/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis id="B907EA4995611870FE1CB3EF11471FF9" box="[500,514,1746,1772]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">2</emphasis>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13482ADE95611870FDFDB3EF11661FF9" box="[533,547,1746,1772]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1063,1085]" captionTargetBox="[334,1055,174,1028]" captionTargetId="figure-291@3.[321,1078,171,1046]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 3. Paradoxus osyridellus: 1 — moth (habitus, dorsal); 2 — male genitalia (ventral view); 3 — aedeagus; 4 — female genitalia; 5 — bursa copulatrix." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6414505" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6414505/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis id="B907EA4995611870FDFDB3EF11661FF9" box="[533,547,1746,1772]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">3</emphasis>
</figureCitation>
). Valva with distinctly narrow apical projection; saccus sclerotized, shorter than valva (
<figureCitation id="13482ADE95611870FDF5B3CF111F1E18" box="[541,602,1778,1805]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[174,207,1289,1311]" captionTargetBox="[331,1074,184,1255]" captionTargetId="figure-183@5.[326,1083,166,1269]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 5. Pseudoplutella porrectella: 1 — moth (habitus, dorsal); 2 — male genitalia (lateral view); 3 — aedeagus; 4 — bursa copulatrix." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6414511" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6414511/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">fig. 5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13482ADE95611870FD8FB3CF11301E19" box="[615,629,1778,1804]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[166,199,1105,1127]" captionTargetBox="[322,1065,191,1089]" captionTargetId="figure-253@2.[317,1074,174,1089]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 2. Argyresthia communana: 1 — forewing pattern; 2–4 — male genitalia (2 — ventral plate, 3 — valva, 4 — aedeagus); 5 — bursa copulatrix." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6414501" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6414501/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis id="B907EA4995611870FD8FB3CF11301E19" box="[615,629,1778,1804]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">2</emphasis>
</figureCitation>
). Aedeagus broadened at the apex, without cornuti (
<figureCitation id="13482ADE95611870FF5EB22F13B71E38" box="[182,242,1810,1837]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[174,207,1289,1311]" captionTargetBox="[331,1074,184,1255]" captionTargetId="figure-183@5.[326,1083,166,1269]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 5. Pseudoplutella porrectella: 1 — moth (habitus, dorsal); 2 — male genitalia (lateral view); 3 — aedeagus; 4 — bursa copulatrix." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6414511" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6414511/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">fig. 5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13482ADE95611870FF16B22F12491E39" box="[254,268,1810,1836]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,1063,1085]" captionTargetBox="[334,1055,174,1028]" captionTargetId="figure-291@3.[321,1078,171,1046]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 3. Paradoxus osyridellus: 1 — moth (habitus, dorsal); 2 — male genitalia (ventral view); 3 — aedeagus; 4 — female genitalia; 5 — bursa copulatrix." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6414505" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6414505/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis id="B907EA4995611870FF16B22F12491E39" box="[254,268,1810,1836]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="28">3</emphasis>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF0C66D395621873FF41B02F17511C3D" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6414514" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6414514" box="[169,1044,1298,1320]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6414514/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" startId="6.[169,202,1298,1320]" targetBox="[322,1064,148,1221]" targetPageId="6">
<paragraph id="8BCC365B95621873FF41B02F17511C3D" blockId="6.[169,1044,1298,1320]" box="[169,1044,1298,1320]" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">
Fig. 6. 
<taxonomicName id="4C734DD895621873FF01B02E12FB1C3D" baseAuthorityName="Mann" baseAuthorityYear="1861" box="[233,446,1299,1320]" class="Insecta" family="Plutellidae" genus="Ypsolopha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albiramella">
<emphasis id="B907EA4995621873FF01B02E12FB1C3D" box="[233,446,1299,1320]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">Ypsolopha albiramella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: 
<emphasis id="B907EA4995621873FE21B02E12911C3D" box="[457,468,1299,1320]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">1</emphasis>
— moth (habitus, dorsal); 
<emphasis id="B907EA4995621873FD3FB02E11A71C3D" box="[727,738,1299,1320]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">2</emphasis>
— male genitalia (lateral view).
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8BCC365B95621873FF33B05F10601C88" blockId="6.[166,1225,1378,1533]" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">
Female genitalia. Apophyses posterior shorter than apophyses anterior. 
<collectingRegion id="49B7F8B995621873FB6DB05E178D1C68" box="[1157,1224,1379,1405]" country="Turkey" name="Bursa" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">Bursa</collectingRegion>
copulatrix of spherical shape, signum absent (
<figureCitation id="13482ADE95621873FD56B0BF11BC1C88" box="[702,761,1410,1437]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[174,207,1289,1311]" captionTargetBox="[331,1074,184,1255]" captionTargetId="figure-183@5.[326,1083,166,1269]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 5. Pseudoplutella porrectella: 1 — moth (habitus, dorsal); 2 — male genitalia (lateral view); 3 — aedeagus; 4 — bursa copulatrix." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6414511" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6414511/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">fig. 5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13482ADE95621873FCEEB0BF10511C89" box="[774,788,1410,1436]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[170,203,990,1012]" captionTargetBox="[236,1125,179,972]" captionTargetId="figure-336@4.[232,1167,171,985]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 4. Kessleria saxifragae: 1 — moth (habitus, dorsal); 2 — male genitalia (ventral view); 3 — aedeagus; 4 — female genitalia; 5 — bursa copulatrix." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6414507" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6414507/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis id="B907EA4995621873FCEEB0BF10511C89" box="[774,788,1410,1436]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">4</emphasis>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCC365B95621873FF33B09E10E11CE9" blockId="6.[166,1225,1378,1533]" pageId="6" pageNumber="29">R e m a r k s. Externally differs from other species by the forewing pattern. Can be distinguished by the elongated apex of valva in the male genitalia; by spherical shape of bursa copulatrix without signum. Rare species in Siberian region.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
